relation: Waxy, non-living layer that repels water and protects it from insects, bacteria, and fungi
Protective, transparent, outer layer that gives the leaf its shape
Elongated, slender cells containing most of the leaf's chlorophyll where most photosynthesis takes palce
Rigid cells that protect the vascular tissue and provide for vascular regrowth
Vascular tissue that transports water and dissolved nutrients throughout the leaf
Vascular tissue that transports sucrose, glucose and other food throughout the leaf
Protective, transparent, outer layer on the underside that gives the leaf its shape and houses stomata
Irregularly shaped cells separated by air spaces that hosue essential gasses
Sausage-shaped cells that control the opening and closing of the stomata by changing shape due to external factors
A pore in the leaf by which water vapor and carbon dioxide enter the leaf to be used for photosynthesis
Microscopic cells that contain chlorophyll and act as the food producers by executing photosynthesis
